It could also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as it deals with natural language processing and semantic relatedness modeling. 

The use of deep neural networks (DNN) suggests that it could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which focuses on machine learning and intelligent systems. 

The paper's focus on modeling topical coherence could also place it in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with developing algorithms that can learn from data. 

Finally, the use of knowledge graphs suggests that it could belong to the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category, which deals with the storage, retrieval, and management of large amounts of data.
